Comments: The CDR loops of the Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR did not change conformation appreciably upon ligation to mCD1d-alpha-GalCer. ""Upon Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR ligation, the alpha-GalCer head group was observed to be shifted by approximately 1 Å. In comparison to the non-liganded Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR [PDB: 2Q86], there was a slight change in the juxta-positioning (9.5°) of the Valpha14 and Vbeta8.2 domains upon ligation. There was minimal movement in the mCD1d upon ligation, with some reorientation of side-chain conformations observed including: Arg 79, Glu 83, Lys 86, Lys 148 from mCD1d . Overall, the lack of conformational change upon Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR-mCD1d-alpha-GalCer ligation, which was also observed in the human NKT TCR-CD1d-alpha-GalCer interaction, typifies the innate characteristics of this interaction mediated by a relatively ‘rigid’ receptor-ligand binding, whereas TCRs typically show a greater degree of plasticity upon ligation with pMHC."" Detailed atomic contacts between TCR and mCD1d-alpha-GalCer are provided in Table 1 and include 10 salt bridges and 8 hydrogen bonds.

Comments: ""Like the Vbeta8.2 NKT TCR-CD1d-alpha-GalCer complex [PDB: 3HE6], the Valpha14-Vbeta7 NKT TCR (this complex) was perched above the F’-pocket of the CD1d-Ag binding cleft, interacting with a similar stretch of residues on mCD1d (76 – 87 and 145 – 153). The footprint of the two TCRs were very similar with the Valpha contacts being dictated by the CDR1alpha and CDR3alpha loops, the former exclusively contacting alpha-GalCer, while the latter making substantial contacts with both mCD1d and alpha-GalCer. However, within these common footprints, there were notable differences in the contacts made between the Vbeta7 and Vbeta8.2 NKT TCRs and CD1d-alpha-GalCer, attributable to sequence differences between the NKT TCRs and differing relative juxta-positioning of the Vbeta8.2/Vbeta7 and Valpha14 domains. In turn, these differences also altered the nature of some of the Valpha14-Jalpha18-mCD1d-alpha-GalCer interactions despite the commonality of the invariant alpha-chain between the two NKT TCRs. Structural differences at the Valpha14-Vbeta7 and Valpha14-Vbeta8.2 interfaces also “transmitted” to alterations in some of the Valpha14-Jalpha18-mCD1d contacts. Specifically, whilst many of the alpha-chain mediated contacts were similar (Table 1), differences in Jalpha18-mediated contacts were observed at the tip of the CDR3alpha loop, namely residues Asp 94alpha, Arg 95alpha, Gly 96alpha, Ser 97alpha, Leu 99alpha and Arg 103alpha."" Detailed contacts are provided in Table 1 and include 9 salt bridges and 3 hydrogen bonds.

Comments: ""Overall, the footprints of the human and mouse NKT TCRs [PDB: 3HE6, 3HE7] were similar, especially between the homologous Vbeta domains (Vbeta11 in humans and Vbeta8.2 in mouse) were compared. Within this common footprint, the following interactions were conserved between the three complexes: Pro 28alpha to alpha-GalCer; Asp 94alpha to alpha-GalCer; Asp 94alpha to Arg 79; Arg 95alpha to alpha-GalCer; Arg 95alpha to Asp 80, Arg 79 & Ser 76; Gly 96alpha to alpha-GalCer; Gly 96alpha to Asp153 (Asp 151 in human CD1d); Ser 97alpha to Val 149 (Val 147 in human CD1d); Leu 99alpha to Val 149; and Tyr 50beta to Glu 83 & Met 87. Nonetheless, a number of differences at the NKT TCR-CD1d interfaces between the three complexes were present, and these were attributable to (i) altered Valpha-Vbeta juxta-positioning (approximately 13 to 15° rotation between human and mouse NKT TCR-CD1d complexes) (ii) sequence differences between the respective CDR loops that mediated CD1d and alpha-GalCer recognition (iii) structural differences between hCD1d and mCD1d, which included an altered positioning of the alpha-GalCer galactose head group due to the presence of a neighbouring Trp 153 (Gly 155 in mCD1d) in hCD1d. Nevertheless, the alpha-galactose head group was sequestered to a similar extent in all three NKT TCR-CD1d-alpha-GalCer structures, with the preservation of the H-bond interactions to the 2’, 3’ and 4’ hydroxyl groups."" Detailed contacts for this structure are not provided.

Comments: ""The NKT TCR adopted an acute docking mode, positioned over the extreme end, directly above the F' pocket of the CD1d-antigen binding cleft, spanning residues 76–89 and 147–151 of the alpha1-helix and the alpha2-helix, respectively. Moreover the NKT TCR bound approximately parallel to the long axis of the CD1d-antigen-binding cleft, which is distinct from the broad range of 'diagonal' footprints observed for MHC class-I-restricted TCRs. Furthermore, of the three MHC class I positions (65, 69 and 155) that are postulated to represent conserved docking points guiding MHC-restriction, no equivalent positions are contacted in the CD1d-restricted interaction. Accordingly, the salient features of MHC–peptide-mediated recognition by a TCR are not preserved in CD1d–lipid-mediated recognition."" Detailed contacts between TCR and CD1-ligand are provided in Table S2 and include 5 salt bridges and 12 hydrogen bonds.

Comments: The 9C2 gammadelta TCR docked orthogonally (87°) over the extreme end of the A′ pocket of CD1d in the gammadelta TCR–CD1d–alpha-GalCer ternary complex. In contrast, all type I NKT TCRs dock in a parallel manner (20°) over the F′ pocket of CD1d, regardless of the identity of the antigen bound in the CD1d cleft [PDB: 2PO6]. As such, there were essentially no common CD1d interacting residues underpinning the gammadelta TCR and type I NKT TCR footprints, with the center of gravity between these two TCRs atop CD1d being approximately 28 Å and 41 Å apart for the Vdelta-Valpha and Vgamma-Vbeta domains, respectively. The mode of gammadelta TCR–CD1d recognition was more reminiscent of how a recently described mouse type II NKT TCR (XV19) docked onto CD1d-sulfatide or CD1d-lysosulfatide [PDB: 4EI5]. The XV19 TCR sat above the A′ pocket of CD1d in an orthogonal docking mode (100°), although the gammadelta TCR was located even further toward the extreme pole of the A′ pocket. Thus, the gammadelta TCR docked onto CD1d-antigen in a distinct manner compared to type I and type II NKT TCR–CD1d recognition thereby highlighting the diverse mechanism by which the alphabeta TCR and gammadelta TCR lineages can interact with CD1d-antigen. Supplementary Table 2 provides 9C2 TCR contacts with CD1d/alpha-GalCer.

Comments: ""BbGL-2c shows the most significant change upon interacting with the TCR. The galactose moiety tilts toward the alpha2 helix by ∼30° (angle of the glycosidic bond), and furthermore, rotates 60° in a clockwise orientation when viewed from above. This causes the 6′ OH group to point toward the alpha1 helix instead of the alpha2 helix. Consequently, the 2′ and 3′ galactose hydroxyl groups are moved closer to the alpha2 helix to form H bonds with Asp153 of mCD1d, as has been observed for alpha-GalCer and for GalA-GSL, even without bound TCR. In contrast, the 2′ OH loses an H bond to Arg79 because it moves away from the alpha1 helix. Overall, BbGL-2c forms less extensive H bonds than either alpha-GalCer or GalA-GSL and has the biggest repositioning of the galactose group upon TCR binding, which involves the breaking of two H bonds, together with the loss of several van der Waals interactions (involving in particular residues Phe70, Tyr73, and Ser76 of mCD1d) while forming four new polar interactions."" Potential hydrogen bonds between the ligand and CD1 residues D153 and T156 are shown in Figure 3; they are not among the calculated contacts. Detailed contacts are provided in Table S1 and include 12 salt bridges and 5 hydrogen bonds between CD1 and TCR and 3 hydrogen bonds between TCR and the ligand (only two of them are among calculated contacts).

Comments: When this OCH complex was compared to alpha-GalCer complex [PDB: 3ARG], the truncated sphingosine tail of OCH did not cause a repositioning of the F′-roof of CD1d. A comparison of the CD1d-Ag binding clefts of the binary CD1d-OCH complex [PDB: 3G08] and this NKT TCR-CD1d-OCH complex showed that the spacer lipid adopted a different conformation and also showed notable displacements (>1 Å) for Leu84, Val85, Lys86, Met87, Met88, and Val149. Further, Leu84 and Leu150 in the binary CD1d-OCH structure adopted very different conformations when compared to that observed in the NKT TCR-CD1d-OCH complex. ""Although we cannot discount that these conformational differences between CD1d-OCH and NKT TCR-CD1d-OCH complexes were attributable to the spacer lipid, our results nevertheless indicated that the NKT TCR can operate via an induced-fit mechanism, whereby the NKT TCR molds the F′-pocket of the CD1d-Ag binding cleft to enable optimal engagement."" The contacts between TCR and antigen-MHC are provided in Table S3. It lists four hydrogen bonds between the antigen and the CD residues N30, G96, and R95; the last one, according to the Table S3, was not observed in [PDB: 3ARG] -- this bond was not among calculated contacts as the atomic distance appears to be too large.

Comments: The structure shows the conserved “parallel"" docking mode of the iNKT TCR on the CD1d-ligand complex. Similar to the antigens previously characterized, the TCR CDR1alpha and CDR3alpha loops exclusively mediate contacts between the TCR and the antigen. In particular, the TCR recognizes the 2′-OH and 3′-OH positions of the hexose ring via H bonds with Gly96 and Asn30 on the alpha chain, highlighting the importance of these two hydroxyl groups on the antigen in the formation of the complex. However, due to the presence of a glucose on Glc-DAG-s2, the 4′ hydroxyl group is no longer able to interact with Asn30 on the alpha chain, in contrast to other galactose-containing glycolipids.Upon TCR ligation, the glucose moiety is shifted by about 30 degrees clockwise around its glycosidic bond to assume a position at the center of the binding groove as observed for other TCR-bound glycolipid antigens. Similar to what has been described for BbGL-2c, this conformational change requires the breaking of several contacts with CD1d and the formation of new hydrogen bonds with the alpha2 helix of CD1d and the TCR alpha chain. In particular, a hydrogen bond with Arg79 on the alpha1 helix is lost while new polar contacts are formed with Asp153 and Thr156 on the alpha2 helix upon TCR binding, resulting in a final orientation conserved among alpha-linked sugars. Contacts are provided in Table S1.

Comments: Contacts are provided in Figure 5 in comparison with the human iNKT TCR–CD1d–alphaGalCer complex [PDB: 3HUJ]. The LPC-reactive iNKT TCR (iNKT-LPC) has a counter-clockwise rotation in relation to the iNKT TCR of the alphaGalCer complex, resulting in shifts of all CDR loops except the CDR3alpha. The positioning of the CDR3alpha loop, as well as many of the contacts established with the CD1d surface, is conserved across the two complexes. Of the 31 contacts that the iNKT-LPC CDR3alpha loop makes with CD1d, 20 (~65%) of these are identical to contacts made by the CDR3alpha loop of the iNKT TCR in the CD1d/alphaGalCer structure. A notable difference in our structure is that the CDR3alpha loop does not contact the LPC ligand. Another key interaction of the iNKT TCR with CD1d–LPC is found in the HV4alpha loop. This loop is typically not involved in ligand recognition in conventional alphabetaTCR and MHCp interactions. Here, the HV4alpha loop appears to play a pivotal role in LPC recognition with the establishment of a salt bridge between the HV4alpha's K70 and the phosphate of the phosphorylcholine headgroup. This interaction likely compensates for the breaking of the salt bridge with CD1d's Arg79 coordinating LPC in the unliganded CD1d–LPC structure.

Comments: Surprisingly, considering the essential role of the terminal sugar of iGb3 in determining its antigenicity, contacts between the Ag and the TCR alpha-chain involve only the beta-Glc and beta-Gal sugars, but not the terminal alpha-Gal. In addition, unlike any previously characterized exogenous iNKT cell Ag, all three CDR loops from the Valpha14 chain are involved in contacting the iGb3 molecule. In particular, Gly96 and Asn30 on the CDR3alpha and CDR1alpha loops, respectively, form H-bonds with the 2′ and 3′ hydroxyl groups of beta-Glc. At the same time, the carbonyl group of both Asn30 on CDR1alpha and Val50 on CDR2alpha, as well as the framework residue Lys68, is interacting with the 6″-OH of the beta-Gal residue. Superposition of the two structures of the mCD1d–iGb3 complex in free [PDB: 2Q7Y] and TCR-bound form (this structure, on mCD1d shows how the TCR is able to squash the trisaccharide head group of iGb3 over the alpha2 helix of CD1d while maintaining the position of the ceramide backbone in a relatively conserved orientation.

Specifically, two tyrosine residues in the CDR2beta loop (Tyr48 and Tyr50) contacted a focused stretch of the alpha1 helix of CD1d, whereas the CDR3alpha loop bridged the CD1d antigen-binding cleft. Accordingly, these data indicate that the antigenicity of beta-linked NKT cell agonists can be attributed to induced interactions with CD1d rather than to direct interactions between the antigen and the NKT cell TCR itself. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table 6.

Comments: Apart from ligand-specific interactions, the MAIT TCR–MR1–epitope complex was virtually identical to the MAIT TCR-MR1–6FP complex [PDB: 4L4T]. Key differences between the complexes included that there was no direct contact between the MAIT TCR and 6-FP, whereas the epitope RL-6-Me-7-OH directly contacts the MAIT TCR. First, while 6-FP formed a Schiff base with Lys43, RL-6-Me-7-OH was non-covalently bound within MR1, which resulted in Lys43 drifting away from the ligand. Second, and surprisingly, the orientation of RL-6-Me-7-OH within the aromatic cradle of MR1 differed dramatically from that of 6-FP. Namely, RL-6-Me-7-OH is rotated ~75° with respect to 6-FP, such that the MR1-mediated contacts between the respective ring systems differ between 6-FP and RL-6-Me-7-OH. The tilted conformation causes the ribityl moiety of RL-6-Me-7-OH to lean towards, and form a series of H-bonds with, Arg9 and Arg94, two evolutionarily conserved residues found within MR1. Contacts are provided in Supplementary Table S2.
